JO  - AMR
SP  - 128
EP  - 133
VL  - 2
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - In this article the author attempts to explain why corporations engage in socially responsible activity. He examines how corporations have begun to focus on social and environmental problems and notes that previous authors have stated this is done simply for public relations-based purposes. He suggests that there is a need to determine the source of corporate morality and uncover the real motivational factors. He offers several reasons why corporations may engage in socially responsible activity such as being led by executives who are truly concerned about social problems, being concerned about what losses they may face if they do not, a form of public relations and advertising and a form of profit seeking behavior.
AB  - In this article the author attempts to explain why corporations engage in socially responsible activity. He examines how corporations have begun to focus on social and environmental problems and notes that previous authors have stated this is done simply for public relations-based purposes. He suggests that there is a need to determine the source of corporate morality and uncover the real motivational factors. He offers several reasons why corporations may engage in socially responsible activity such as being led by executives who are truly concerned about social problems, being concerned about what losses they may face if they do not, a form of public relations and advertising and a form of profit seeking behavior.
